"""
MKT Context Commentary — 2 Kings chapters 15–17
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-2kings-15-17.py

Ch 15: The parade of kings — 6 kings of Israel (rapid succession and Assyrian pressure),
       Azariah/Uzziah (52-year Judah reign), Jotham. Tiglath-pileser III's first deportations.
Ch 16: Ahaz — worst of Judah's kings; Syro-Ephraimite war (Isa 7 backdrop); Damascus altar;
       tribute-driven temple modifications.
Ch 17: Fall of Samaria (722 BCE); extended theological explanation (vv7-23, unique in Kings);
       Samaritan resettlement and syncretism.

Key ANE/historical context:
- 15:5: Uzziah's leprosy (2 Chr 26:16-21) — unauthorized incense-offering in the temple
- 15:19: Pul = Tiglath-pileser III (confirmed by Babylonian king-list and Assyrian annals)
- 15:29: First Assyrian deportations — Isaiah 9:1 allusion to Galilee's darkness
- 16:3: "Pass through the fire" — child sacrifice; ANE Molech cult / Tophet in the Hinnom valley
- 16:7-9: Ahaz's vassal formula "I am your servant and your son" — diplomatic submission language
- 16:10: Damascus altar — Ahaz commissions a pagan altar design; Urijah's compliance
- 17:6: Sargon II's annals confirm Samaria's fall and deportation of 27,290 inhabitants
- 17:30-31: Replacement-population deities identified in Mesopotamian sources
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

KINGS2 = {
  "15": {
    "1": "<p>Azariah (also called Uzziah in 2 Chr 26 and the prophetic books) begins a 52-year reign in Judah in the 27th year of Jeroboam II of Israel. The co-regency system in Judah (with Azariah serving as co-regent under Amaziah before taking the throne) explains the complex chronological cross-referencing throughout 2 Kings 15. The two names — <em>ʿAzaryāh</em> (YHWH has helped) and <em>ʿUzziyyāh</em> (YHWH is my strength) — may reflect a personal name and a throne name respectively, or a scribal variation; both appear in the prophetic tradition, with Isaiah identifying himself as active from Uzziah's reign onward (Isa 1:1), contemporary also with Hosea and Amos.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Azariah's 52-year reign (c. 791–739 BCE) is the longest in the divided monarchy after Solomon's 40 years, spanning nearly the entire ministries of Amos, Hosea, Isaiah, and Micah. The age at accession (16) and long reign created a period of relative stability for Judah, contrasting sharply with the rapid succession of northern kings that fills the rest of this chapter. Archaeological evidence from this period shows Judah's expansion — Azariah/Uzziah rebuilt Elath (v14:22), fortified the Negev, and developed copper-smelting operations at Timna — consistent with the Chronicles account of his military and agricultural achievements (2 Chr 26:6-15).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The evaluative formula for Azariah — <em>hayyāšār bᵉʿênê YHWH kᵉḵōl ʾăšer ʿāśāh ʾăḇîhû ʾĂmaṣyāhû</em>, 'right in the eyes of YHWH as all his father Amaziah had done' — places him in the qualified positive line of Judah's kings. The qualification (v4) that high places remained is the standard mark of incompleteness for every Judah king except Hezekiah and Josiah; the Deuteronomist's criterion is not merely personal piety but the centralization of worship that the law demands.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The high places (<em>bāmôt</em>) were local shrines used for sacrifice and incense throughout the pre-exilic period. Archaeological evidence shows that Israelite domestic and local cult sites with standing stones, libation bowls, and altars existed alongside the Jerusalem temple throughout the monarchic period. The persistence of high places through the otherwise good reigns of Asa, Jehoshaphat, Joash, Amaziah, and Azariah indicates that centralization of worship was an ideal articulated in Deuteronomy but not practically enforced until Hezekiah (18:4) and Josiah (23:8-9). The Deuteronomist presents the high places not as pagan worship but as a dilution of YHWH's exclusive claim to the Jerusalem sanctuary.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The LORD's striking Azariah with <em>ṣāraʿat</em> (conventionally 'leprosy' — the skin-purity condition of Lev 13-14) is given here without explanation, but 2 Chr 26:16-21 provides the backstory: Uzziah entered the temple to burn incense on the incense altar, a function reserved exclusively for the Aaronic priests. When confronted by 80 priests, the <em>ṣāraʿat</em> broke out on his forehead in the temple, and he was rushed out. The punishment is priestly-boundary theology in action: the king who crosses the sacral boundary between royal and priestly functions is marked with the very condition (impurity) that most clearly excludes from the temple (Lev 13:46). Living in a <em>bêt haḥopšît</em> (a separate/free house — a place of quarantine) until death, Azariah was effectively excluded from both cult and court; Jotham governed as regent. The leprosy is the year Isaiah sees the LORD in the temple (Isa 6:1: 'In the year king Uzziah died') — the king's removal from the temple becomes the occasion for the prophet's vision of the divine king.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The formulaic referral to the Book of the Chronicles of the Kings of Judah (<em>sēper diḇrê hayyāmîm lᵉmalkê yᵉhûḏāh</em>) appears 15 times in 1-2 Kings. This is a royal annals source distinct from the canonical Chronicles; the phrase acknowledges that the Deuteronomistic History is a selective retelling that filters the richer archival record for theological purposes. The formula functions as both a citation and a disclaimer: the Deuteronomist is not writing a complete political history but a theological assessment.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Azariah's burial in the city of David follows the standard formula for Judah's kings. The longer version in 2 Chr 26:23 specifies that he was buried 'in the burial field that belonged to the kings, for they said, He is a leper.' Even in death, the priestly-purity logic continued: a leper was not buried in the royal tombs proper but in an associated field. Archaeological exploration of the city of David area has identified rock-cut tombs from the monarchic period; a second-temple-era inscription reading 'hither were brought the bones of Uzziah, king of Judah — not to be opened' was found in the 1930s, suggesting his remains were reinterred in the late second-temple period.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Zechariah son of Jeroboam II begins what will be the final chapter of the Jehu dynasty. The synchronization to Azariah's 38th year continues the dual-timeline structure of 2 Kings. The six-month reign is one of the shortest in the book; only Zimri's seven days (1 Kgs 16:15) was briefer. The rapid collapse of Jeroboam II's dynasty — he was the northern kingdom's most powerful king, expanding Israel's borders to near-Solomonic scale (14:25) — illustrates the instability that follows unchecked by prophetic assessment: 2 Kgs 14:26-27 states YHWH saw Israel's bitter affliction and had not said he would blot out the name of Israel, yet the dynasty ends in assassination two generations later.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The evaluative formula for Zechariah — <em>rāʿ bᵉʿênê YHWH... lōʾ sār mēḥaṭṭāʾôt Yarāḇᵉʿām ben-Nᵉḇāṭ ʾăšer heḥĕṭîʾ ʾet-Yiśrāʾēl</em>, 'evil in the sight of YHWH... did not turn from the sins of Jeroboam son of Nebat who made Israel to sin' — is the standard negative formula applied to all 19 northern kings. The 'sins of Jeroboam' refers to the golden calves at Bethel and Dan (1 Kgs 12:28-30), installed as an alternative pilgrimage center to prevent northern subjects from going to Jerusalem; the Deuteronomist treats this as the foundational sin that set the north on the trajectory toward exile.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Shallum son of Jabesh assassinates Zechariah publicly — <em>wayyakkēhû qāḇāl ʿām</em>, 'struck him before the people' — and seizes the throne. The phrase suggests a public, possibly staged execution rather than a private conspiracy; the 'before the people' detail may indicate a public forum. The name Jabesh links Shallum to Jabesh-gilead, the Transjordanian city that had loyal connections to the house of Saul (1 Sam 31:11-13) — possibly suggesting Shallum represented a Gileadite faction opposed to Jeroboam's legacy. His month-long reign is one of five conspirators who take the northern throne in this chapter alone.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The formulaic summary for Zechariah notes that his acts 'are written in the Book of the Chronicles of the Kings of Israel.' The fact that a six-month reign receives this formula (normally signaling significant recorded history) may be a mechanical application of the formula rather than indicating substantial historical records. The Deuteronomist's interest in Zechariah is primarily the word-fulfillment formula that follows in v12.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The fulfillment notice — <em>hûʾ dᵉḇar YHWH ʾăšer dibber ʾel-Yēhûʾ lēʾmōr bᵉnê rᵉḇîʿîm yēšᵉḇû lᵉḵā ʿal kissēʾ Yiśrāʾēl</em>, 'this is the word of YHWH that he spoke to Jehu: your sons to the fourth generation shall sit on the throne of Israel' — cross-references 2 Kgs 10:30, where YHWH rewarded Jehu's purge of Ahab's house with a four-generation dynasty. The counting: Jehu → Jehoahaz → Joash → Jeroboam II → Zechariah (4th generation from Jehu). The Deuteronomist inserts this fulfillment notice with the formula <em>wayᵉhî kēn</em>, 'and so it was,' emphasizing that the political turbulence is not chaos but YHWH's word working through history with precision.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Shallum's one-month reign in Samaria (in the 39th year of Uzziah) makes him one of the most ephemeral kings in the Bible. The text offers no theological evaluation of Shallum beyond his removal by Menahem — his reign is too short for the standard evaluation formula. The year of Uzziah synchronization again requires co-regency calculations to resolve the apparent contradictions between northern and southern chronologies throughout this chapter.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Menahem son of Gadi comes from Tirzah — the former capital of the northern kingdom before Omri built Samaria (1 Kgs 16:23-24). Tirzah (identified with Tell el-Far'ah North) was the capital under Jeroboam I, Baasha, Elah, and Zimri; the fact that Menahem originates there may suggest a competing power base in the old northern capital. He goes up (<em>wayyaʿal</em>) from Tirzah to Samaria, a geographical and political ascent; the verb <em>nāḵāh</em> (struck him down) followed by <em>wayᵉmîtēhû</em> (killed him) are the verbs of judicial or military execution used throughout these coup narratives.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The summary for Shallum again cites the Book of the Chronicles — uniquely, it also specifically references the conspiracy (<em>qišrô ʾăšer qāšar</em>) he carried out, perhaps indicating that the archival record contained a detailed conspiracy account. The Deuteronomist is not interested in the conspiracy's details; his interest is in the pattern of YHWH's word being fulfilled and then the spiral of instability that follows the Jehu dynasty's end.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Menahem's atrocity at Tiphsah — striking the city and <em>yᵉbaqaʿ ʾet kol hāhārôt ʾăšer bāhh</em>, 'ripping open all the pregnant women in it' — is one of the most brutal acts recorded in Kings. Tiphsah is probably Tappuah (2 Kgs 15:16 LXX reads Taphsah/Tappuah), a city on the Ephraim-Manasseh border that refused to open its gates. The Assyrian reliefs from Tiglath-pileser III and Sennacherib's campaigns depict similar acts of warfare — the disemboweling of pregnant women was an Assyrian siege atrocity (Amos 1:13 condemns Ammon for the same act against Gilead). The fact that an Israelite king commits this act against a fellow Israelite city suggests Menahem's regime was brutal even by ANE military standards; his subsequent decade-long reign (v17) may have been maintained precisely through terror.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Menahem's ten-year reign (c. 752–742 BCE) is one of the longer northern reigns in the post-Jehu period. The synchronization to Azariah's 39th year places him in the era of Tiglath-pileser III's rise — the Assyrian king who would fundamentally reshape the political geography of the Levant. Menahem's name (<em>mᵉnaḥēm</em> — comforter, consoler) is ironic given the atrocity of v16 and the tribute payment of v19-20.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The standard negative evaluation — 'did not turn from the sins of Jeroboam son of Nebat who made Israel to sin, all his days' — is applied mechanically but with the added temporal qualifier 'all his days.' For the Deuteronomist, Menahem's ten years of evil are weighed identically with Zechariah's six months; the criterion is apostasy, not duration.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Pul king of Assyria is Tiglath-pileser III (ruled 745–727 BCE), one of the most transformative figures in ancient Near Eastern history. 'Pul' is his Babylonian throne name, confirmed by the Babylonian king-list (ANET 272) where he appears as 'Pulu.' His 15-year campaign program reorganized the Assyrian empire through systematic deportation and provincial restructuring. Menahem's tribute of 1,000 talents of silver — raised by a 50-shekel head-tax on every <em>gibbôr ḥayil</em> (man of wealth, substantial landowner) — is enormous: at c. 34 grams per shekel, 1,000 talents = c. 34 tons of silver, paid to secure Assyrian backing (<em>hāyᵉtāh yādô ʾittô</em>, 'his hand was with him') and strengthen his grip on the kingdom. Tiglath-pileser's own annals (Annals 11–13) confirm receiving tribute from 'Menahem of Samaria' (Menihimme ša Samerina).</p>",
    "20": "<p>Menahem's tax mechanism — <em>wayyôṣēʾ mᵉnaḥēm ʾet hakkesep ʿal Yiśrāʾēl ʿal kol gibbôrê haḥayil lātēt lᵉmelek ʾaššûr ḥămiššîm šeqel kāsep lāʾîš ʾeḥāḏ</em>, 'Menahem brought out the silver from Israel, from all the wealthy men, to give to the king of Assyria — fifty shekels of silver per man' — indicates a census-based extraction targeting landed wealth. Fifty shekels was roughly the price of a slave (Lev 27:3 sets 50 shekels as the redemption value of a male aged 20-60), suggesting the tribute was calibrated to the labor-value of the tax base. The Assyrian withdrawal (<em>wayyāšāḇ wayyᵉlōʾ hāyāh šām</em>, 'he turned and did not remain there') confirms that the tribute achieved its purpose: Menahem bought continued kingship at enormous cost to his wealthiest subjects, a pattern of Assyrian vassal management that would accelerate under later northern kings.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The formulaic summary for Menahem's ten-year reign refers to his acts in the Book of Chronicles of the Kings of Israel. The Deuteronomist's brevity here — despite Menahem's long reign and significant events (the first Assyrian tribute payment from Israel) — reflects the theological framework: the archival record is acknowledged, but only acts bearing on YHWH's evaluation of the king's faithfulness receive extended treatment.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Menahem's succession by his son Pekahiah is one of only three cases of father-son succession in the northern kingdom after the Jehu dynasty; the others were Jeroboam I to Nadab and Baasha to Elah. The relative stability is notable given the chaos before and after: Menahem killed Shallum, but his own death appears to be natural (he 'rested with his fathers' rather than being killed), and Pekahiah inherits rather than seizes the throne.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Pekahiah (YHWH has opened his eyes) reigns two years (c. 742–740 BCE) — the year synchronization with Azariah's 50th year continues. His brief reign in Samaria ends in assassination, one of three consecutive northern kings killed by conspirators in this chapter. The instability of the northern throne in this period contrasts with the relative longevity of Judah's kings and illustrates the centrifugal tendency of the northern kingdom without a stable dynastic principle.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The standard negative evaluation formula is applied to Pekahiah: 'did not turn from the sins of Jeroboam son of Nebat who made Israel to sin.' The repeated formula, applied now to six consecutive northern kings in this chapter, creates a cumulative rhetorical effect: the pattern of apostasy is unbroken from the kingdom's founding, building toward the Deuteronomist's theological verdict in ch 17 that exile was the inevitable consequence of this unbroken trajectory.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Pekah son of Remaliah (<em>śālîš</em> — third officer, a military rank, possibly 'charioteer') conspires against Pekahiah with fifty Gileadite warriors and kills him in the inner citadel (<em>ʾarmon</em> — the fortified inner complex of the palace) together with Argob and Arieh. Argob and Arieh are otherwise unknown; the detail that they were killed alongside the king may indicate they were bodyguards or court officials caught in the coup. Pekah's Gileadite base (like Shallum's possible connection to Jabesh-gilead) suggests ongoing regional tension between the Transjordanian tribal territory and the Samaritan court. Pekah's name means 'he has opened/delivered' — ironic given his eventual fate (v30).</p>",
    "26": "<p>The summary for Pekahiah follows the standard formula. The brevity of his reign (two years) and the lack of any distinguishing events in the Kings account means the Chronicles citation functions primarily as an acknowledgment that a fuller record existed, not as a pointer to significant content the Deuteronomist has omitted.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Pekah's 20-year reign (c. 740–732 BCE) is puzzling chronologically: if he reigned 20 years but the Assyrian annals confirm his removal by Hoshea around 732 BCE, the 20-year figure may include the period he was a rival claimant or commander in Gilead before seizing Samaria. Some scholars suggest Pekah may have claimed kingship from a Transjordanian base for part of the 20 years, with the Samaria-based Menahem/Pekahiah regime representing a competing claim. The synchronization to Azariah's 52nd year is consistent with the co-regency calculations required throughout this chapter.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The negative evaluation formula applied to Pekah is identical to that for Menahem and Pekahiah. The unrelenting application of the same formula to kings of differing character, reign length, and political significance reflects the Deuteronomist's conviction that the northern kingdom's idolatry was a systemic problem rooted in the golden-calf institutions of Jeroboam I, not reducible to individual kings' choices. Even Pekah's pro-Egyptian coalition policy (against Ahaz of Judah) and his political resistance to Assyria — arguably a more militarily aggressive posture than Menahem's tribute payments — receives the same formula.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Tiglath-pileser III's campaign against Pekah's territories (c. 733–732 BCE) is the first large-scale Assyrian deportation from the land of Israel. The specific territories listed — Ijon, Abel-beth-maacah, Janoah, Kedesh, Hazor, Gilead, and Galilee ('all the land of Naphtali') — correspond to the northernmost and Transjordanian territories. Tiglath-pileser's annals (Iraq 18, 117-129) confirm this campaign: '...the wide land of Naphtali, in its entirety, I brought within the border of Assyria.' The deportation of the Galilean and Transjordanian population is the historical background for Isaiah 9:1: 'In the earlier time he brought contempt upon the land of Zebulun and the land of Naphtali, but in the later time he will make it glorious — by the way of the sea, beyond the Jordan, Galilee of the nations.' Matthew 4:15-16 cites this verse as fulfilled in Jesus' ministry in Galilee — the first territory plunged into Assyrian darkness is the first to receive the light of the Messiah.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Hoshea son of Elah's conspiracy against Pekah is confirmed in Tiglath-pileser III's annals: 'They overthrew their king Pekah and I placed Hoshea as king over them' (ANET 284). The Assyrian king effectively installed Hoshea as a vassal, with Hoshea likely approaching Tiglath-pileser to gain Assyrian backing for the coup in exchange for tribute and submission. The synchronization note — 'in the 20th year of Jotham son of Uzziah' — creates another chronological complexity, since Jotham's reign was only 16 years (v33); this likely reflects the co-regency period under Azariah rather than actual years from Jotham's sole reign.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The formulaic summary for Pekah closes his entry. The archival source presumably contained the details of his Syro-Ephraimite coalition against Ahaz (ch 16, and Isaiah 7-8) and his anti-Assyrian policy; the Deuteronomist's theological assessment displaces this political history with the sin formula.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Jotham son of Uzziah begins his Judah reign in the second year of Pekah. The cross-synchronization of northern and southern kings continues; both Azariah and Jotham reigned simultaneously with Pekah, requiring careful chronological resolution. Jotham is one of the few Judah kings given an unqualified positive evaluation (with the exception of the high-places caveat); his name means 'YHWH is complete/upright.'</p>",
    "33": "<p>Jotham's 16-year reign (c. 750–735 BCE) and age at accession (25) place his rule in the later phase of the Assyrian ascendancy. His mother's name Jerusha daughter of Zadok is a priestly lineage — the name Zadok (righteous) links to the Solomonic high-priestly line; a mother of priestly descent may have contributed to Jotham's more strictly observant reign. The sixteen years count from Jotham's sole reign; during the earlier period he served as regent for his leprous father (v5).</p>",
    "34": "<p>The evaluation formula for Jotham — <em>kᵉḵōl ʾăšer ʿāśāh ʾăḇîhû ʿUzziyyāhû</em>, 'as all his father Uzziah had done' — is positive but comparative rather than absolute. Jotham is qualified good; he did as Uzziah, and Uzziah was good despite his eventual transgression. The Deuteronomist's use of Uzziah as the reference point rather than David may indicate that within the post-Uzziah Judah tradition, Uzziah/Azariah set the standard for the most recent qualified-good king.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Jotham's most noted building achievement was constructing the upper gate of the house of the LORD (<em>šaʿar bêt YHWH hāʿelyôn</em>), confirmed in 2 Chr 27:3 which adds further building activity in Jerusalem and Judah. The 'upper gate' is the northern gate of the inner temple court, probably the gate mentioned in Ezekiel 9:2 and Jer 20:2; it connected the temple to the king's house in the royal complex. The persistence of the high places (v35b) means even Jotham's building achievement at the temple coexists with the unauthorized local cult sites that the Deuteronomist views as illegitimate alternatives to centralized worship.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The formulaic summary for Jotham points to the Book of the Chronicles. 2 Chronicles 27:5-6 provides additional content: Jotham defeated the Ammonites and received significant tribute (100 talents of silver, 10,000 cors of wheat, 10,000 cors of barley), and his strength was attributed to ordering his ways before YHWH. The Deuteronomist omits these political and military details in favor of the theological evaluation.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The notice that YHWH 'began to send' (<em>hēḥēl YHWH lᵉšallēaḥ</em>) Rezin king of Aram and Pekah king of Israel against Judah is a proleptic note introducing the Syro-Ephraimite war that dominates ch 16. The verb <em>hēḥēl</em> (began) signals that the full pressure comes in Ahaz's reign; under Jotham, the threat is initiating. The coalition of Aram and the northern kingdom against Judah is the historical background for Isaiah 7-8 (the Immanuel oracle), in which Isaiah assures Ahaz that the two smoldering stump kingdoms (Isa 7:4) will not succeed in displacing the house of David.</p>",
    "38": "<p>Jotham's death and burial 'in the city of David his father' follows the standard Judah burial formula. His son Ahaz succeeds him — one of Judah's most theologically compromised kings. The transition from the last qualified-good king (before Hezekiah) to the most apostate king since Ahaz is dramatic; the Syro-Ephraimite pressure brewing at the end of Jotham's reign (v37) becomes the crisis that drives Ahaz's disastrous Assyrian alliance.</p>"
  },
  "16": {
    "1": "<p>Ahaz son of Jotham begins his reign in the 17th year of Pekah (c. 735 BCE). The name Ahaz (<em>ʾāḥāz</em> — he has grasped/held) is a shortened form of Jehoahaz (YHWH has grasped); the omission of the divine element in the regnal name is notable — he is not identified with YHWH in either his personal or throne name. His accession coincides with the height of the Syro-Ephraimite coalition threat and the period of Isaiah's most intense prophetic activity (Isa 7-12 is largely Ahaz-era material).</p>",
    "2": "<p>Ahaz's negative evaluation — 'he did not do what was right in the eyes of the LORD his God, as his ancestor David had done' — is the Deuteronomist's worst Judah verdict: failing even the Davidic standard that is the benchmark for southern kings. The qualifier 'his God' (<em>ʾelōhāyw</em> rather than simply 'the LORD') may carry a hint of irony: YHWH is Ahaz's God by covenant, even though Ahaz does not act accordingly. The contrast with David frames Ahaz as a covenant failure at the royal level.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'He made his son pass through the fire' (<em>heʿĕḇîr ʾet-bᵉnô bāʾēš</em>) is the Kings formula for child sacrifice, almost certainly at the Tophet in the valley of the son of Hinnom (Gê-Hinnom / Gehenna), south of Jerusalem. This practice — the sacrifice of children to Molech or the 'king' deity — is condemned in Lev 18:21, 20:2-5 and Deut 18:10. The Tophet was a fire installation where children were burned as sacrifices; Jer 7:31 and 19:5 describe it as something YHWH never commanded and never entered his mind. Ahaz's child sacrifice is unique among Judah's kings (though Manasseh repeats it, 21:6); it places him in the category of the Canaanite nations the LORD drove out (<em>kᵉtôʿᵃḇōt haggôyim ʾăšer hôrîš YHWH</em>) — the very logic by which Israel's own conduct triggers exile.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The high places, hills, and 'under every green tree' (<em>taḥat kol ʿēṣ raʿănān</em>) describes the full range of Canaanite cult topography. The 'green tree' formula appears in Deut 12:2, Jer 2:20, 3:6, 17:2, and Ezek 6:13 as a marker of syncretic Israelite worship in Canaanite cultic locations — high places, hilltop shrines, and tree-shaded groves where Baal and Asherah worship was practiced. For the Deuteronomist, Ahaz's participation in these sites represents a full reversion to pre-Conquest Canaanite religion, completing the indictment of v3.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The Syro-Ephraimite war (c. 735–732 BCE): Rezin of Aram and Pekah of Israel march against Jerusalem and besiege it (<em>wayyāṣūrû ʿal ʾāḥāz wᵉlōʾ yāḵᵉlû lᵉhillāḥēm</em>, 'they besieged Ahaz but could not fight against him'). The coalition's goal, specified in Isa 7:6, was to depose Ahaz and install a non-Davidic king ('the son of Tabeel') — effectively ending the Davidic dynasty. The failure to conquer is the specific fulfillment point of Isaiah's Immanuel oracle (Isa 7:14-17): before the child can distinguish good from evil, the two kings (Rezin and Pekah) before whom Ahaz dreads will be deserted. The oracle links the coalition's failure not to Ahaz's military strength but to YHWH's protection of the Davidic house.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Rezin's recovery of Elath for Aram — expelling the Judeans (<em>ʾet hāyᵉhûḏîm</em>) and settling Syrians there — represents a strategic loss for Judah. Elath (Eloth, modern Aqaba) was the Red Sea port recovered by Azariah/Uzziah (2 Kgs 14:22), giving Judah access to trade routes to Arabia and East Africa. Rezin's seizure closes this trade access and shifts control of the Arabah copper trade (Timna region) away from Judah. The detail that 'Syrians came to Elath and lived there to this day' suggests the note was written before Tiglath-pileser conquered Damascus (v9), or that Syrian settlement persisted through subsequent changes of imperial control.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Ahaz's message to Tiglath-pileser — <em>ʿaḇdᵉḵā ûḇinᵉḵā ʾānî</em>, 'I am your servant and your son' — is the full vassal-submission formula of ANE diplomacy. The double phrase ('servant' and 'son') may reflect standard Assyrian protocol for requesting military aid; Assyrian administrative texts use similar formulas for vassal relationships. The 'servant' terminology signals complete political submission (tribute, military cooperation, loyalty oaths); the 'son' terminology invokes the adoption metaphor used in ancient treaties, where the suzerain adopts the vassal as a son to formalize the relationship. This formula is the inverse of Israel's covenant language: YHWH is Israel's father and Israel his son (Exod 4:22-23, Hos 11:1) — Ahaz transfers the covenant-son relationship from YHWH to the Assyrian king.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Ahaz takes silver and gold from the temple treasury and royal palace to pay tribute to Tiglath-pileser. The temple treasure had survived (and been replenished) through several earlier extractions (1 Kgs 14:26, 15:18, 2 Kgs 12:18, 14:14), but each extraction weakens the institution. The use of temple gold as political currency — buying Assyrian protection — is theologically pointed: YHWH's sanctuary funds the appeal to a human king rather than to YHWH himself. Isaiah's challenge to Ahaz (Isa 7:10-12: ask a sign from YHWH) is Ahaz's road not taken; instead, he bankrolls Assyria.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Tiglath-pileser responds to Ahaz's appeal by capturing Damascus (732 BCE), deporting its population to Kir (<em>wayyaglēh qîrāh</em>), and executing Rezin. The deportation to Kir (a region in Mesopotamia, possibly near the Kur River in western Iran) is theologically ironic in light of Amos 9:7, where YHWH states he brought the Syrians up from Kir — so the Assyrian deportation reverses the Aramean 'exodus,' returning Aram to its origin-point. Damascus's fall ends the 300-year Aramean kingdom that had been Israel's most persistent enemy from Ben-hadad I (1 Kgs 15:18) through Hazael; the city that Elijah anointed Hazael to destabilize Israel is now rubble. Ahaz's strategy worked politically but at the cost of Judah's sovereignty and YHWH's covenant.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Ahaz's visit to Damascus to meet Tiglath-pileser occasions one of the most theologically charged acts in Kings: he sees the Damascus altar (<em>hammizbeaḥ ʾăšer bᵉḏammāśeq</em>) and sends Urijah the priest the design and pattern (<em>taḇnît hammizbeaḥ wᵉḏimyôtô lᵉḵol-maʿᵃśēhû</em>). The altar design was likely Aramaean or Assyrian; Ahaz probably encountered it at the victory ceremony after Damascus's fall. The instruction to replicate it precisely — exact design, all details — represents a religious syncretism driven by political alignment: the king who submitted to Assyria also submitted his worship space to the altar associated with Assyrian-aligned religion. Urijah (possibly the same prophet mentioned as a witness to Isaiah's oracle in Isa 8:2) is a compliant priest who executes the commission without recorded objection.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Urijah's speed — the altar was ready before the king returned from Damascus — reflects efficient compliance with royal command. The narrative detail serves two functions: it demonstrates Urijah's complete obedience to Ahaz over against YHWH's law, and it creates the temporal frame in which the old altar is operational right up to the point of the new altar's inauguration. The phrase 'exactly as King Ahaz had specified' (<em>kᵉḵōl ʾăšer šālaḥ hammelek ʾāḥāz me-Dammāśeq kēn ʿāśāh ʾUriyyāh hakkōhēn</em>) emphasizes human rather than divine specification as the altar's design authority.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Ahaz approaches and mounts the new altar (<em>wayyiqraḇ hammelek ʾel-hammizbeaḥ wayyaʿal ʿālāyw</em>) — a royal act of cult inauguration. The verb <em>qāraḇ</em> (approached, drew near) is the same term used for priestly approach to the altar; Ahaz functions as priest-king at his pagan altar installation, mirroring (and inverting) the priestly approach at the legitimate cult. The inauguration follows the proper sequence of offerings (v13), but on an altar of entirely wrong provenance.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The offering sequence on the Damascus altar — burnt offering (<em>ʿōlāh</em>), grain offering (<em>minḥāh</em>), drink offering (<em>nesek</em>), and blood of peace offerings (<em>šelamîm</em>) — is the standard Levitical offering sequence from Lev 1-7. The irony is that Ahaz uses legitimately designated offering categories on an illegitimately sourced altar. The peace-offering blood splashed (<em>yizrōq</em> — the same verb used for the legitimate altar in Lev 1:5) indicates the offerings themselves are correctly performed; the problem is the altar's origin and the act's displacement of the Solomonic bronze altar.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The bronze altar (Solomon's original altar, 1 Kgs 8:64) is moved from its position between the new altar and the temple entrance to the north side. The demotion is architectural theology: the Damascus altar occupies the primary position (south face, facing Jerusalem's sun-oriented geography), while YHWH's bronze altar is lateralized to a secondary position. Ahaz's qualification — 'I will offer on it later for my personal inquiry' (<em>ʾăḇaqēš bô</em>, v15) — may suggest the bronze altar was retained for divination (consulting YHWH by lot or sacrifice) rather than public worship, a further degradation of its function.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Ahaz's instructions to Urijah reorder the entire offering system around the Damascus altar: all official royal and public offerings (<em>ʿōlat habbōqer... minḥat hāʿereḇ... ʿōlat hammelek... minḥātô... ʿōlat kol ʿam hāʾāreṣ... minḥātām wᵉniskêhem</em>) are to be conducted on the new altar. The blood disposal instruction (<em>kol dam ʿōlāh wᵉḵol dam zeḇaḥ tizrōq ʿālāyw</em>) makes the Damascus altar the official altar of both royal and popular worship. The bronze altar is reserved — ambiguously — for the king's 'personal inquiry' (<em>ʾaḇaqēš</em>), possibly divination, possibly a vestigial YHWH-consultation that Ahaz retains for private use while publicly orienting the national cult toward the Damascus design.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Urijah's complete compliance — 'Urijah the priest did according to all that King Ahaz commanded' — is the narrative's damning assessment of the priesthood. The high priest who should be the guardian of Levitical law becomes the executor of royal religious policy. Ezekiel 22:26 indicts the priests for doing violence to YHWH's law and failing to distinguish between holy and common; Ahaz's Urijah is an instance of that failure at the most senior level.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Ahaz's dismantling of the bronze wheeled stands (<em>mᵉḵônôt</em>) and removal of the laver-basins, plus lifting the great bronze sea (<em>hayyām hanᵉḥōšet</em>) off its twelve bronze oxen and placing it on a stone pavement — are all modifications to Solomon's temple furnishings (1 Kgs 7:27-39, 23-26). The bronze sea was an enormous cast-metal basin representing the cosmic sea and providing water for priestly purification. Lifting it from the twelve oxen (representing the twelve tribes supporting the sea) onto a stone pavement deprives the installation of its symbolic significance. The motivation given in v18 is compliance with Assyrian demands; the practical purpose was likely to extract valuable bronze for tribute payment or to conform temple layout to Assyrian aesthetic expectations at an imperial inspection.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The 'covered Sabbath walkway' (<em>mûsaḵ haššabbāt</em> — the Sabbath canopy or colonnade, possibly a sheltered portico for Sabbath assemblies) and the 'king's outer entrance' are modified 'on account of the king of Assyria' (<em>mippᵉnê melek ʾaššûr</em>). This is the only explicit mention of Assyrian architectural compliance in the temple account. The modifications may have been required for an Assyrian vassal inspection tour or to provide access for Assyrian imperial officials. The removal of a specifically Sabbath-associated structure is theologically charged: the Sabbath is the covenant sign between YHWH and Israel (Exod 31:13, 16-17); removing the Sabbath walkway is an architectural erasure of the covenant marker.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The formulaic summary for Ahaz refers to the Book of the Chronicles of the Kings of Judah. The Chronicles account (2 Chr 28) is considerably longer: Ahaz also suffered military defeats from Aram, Israel, Edom, and the Philistines — a comprehensive series of covenant curses (Deut 28:25) — and the text of 2 Chr 28:16-21 emphasizes that the Assyrian tribute did not help him. The Deuteronomist's account focuses on the religious apostasy; the Chronicles account adds the political-military dimensions of divine judgment.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Ahaz's burial in the city of David does not follow the standard 'buried with his fathers' formula; 2 Chr 28:27 specifies that 'they buried him in the city, in Jerusalem, for they did not bring him into the tombs of the kings of Israel' — he was denied the royal burial honor. Hezekiah his son succeeds him; the contrast between father and son will be extreme. Ahaz represents the nadir of Judah's preexilic apostasy; Hezekiah will be described as 'like him there was none among all the kings of Judah after him, nor among those before him' (18:5) — the highest Davidic praise, assigned to the son of the most compromised king.</p>"
  },
  "17": {
    "1": "<p>Hoshea son of Elah begins his reign in Samaria in the 12th year of Ahaz (c. 732 BCE), reigning nine years (c. 732–723 BCE). He is the last king of the northern kingdom — 19 kings from Jeroboam I to Hoshea, none of whom turned from the sins of Jeroboam. Hoshea's name (<em>hôšēaʿ</em> — salvation, deliverance) is the same root as Joshua and Jesus; the final northern king bears the name of salvation but delivers his kingdom into captivity. He was installed by Tiglath-pileser III after killing Pekah (15:30) and was from the beginning an Assyrian vassal.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The evaluative formula for Hoshea is uniquely qualified: 'He did what was evil in the sight of the LORD, though not to the degree of the kings of Israel before him' (<em>rāʿ bᵉʿênê YHWH raq lōʾ ḵᵉmalkê Yiśrāʾēl ʾăšer hāyû lᵉpānāyw</em>). This is the only northern king to receive a qualified negative evaluation. The basis of the qualification is unclear — possibly Hoshea permitted more direct YHWH worship, possibly the Deuteronomist is acknowledging that even within the unbroken negative trajectory there were degrees of apostasy. The qualification does not save Hoshea or the kingdom; the trajectory toward exile is unaffected by relative improvement.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Shalmaneser V (ruled 727–722 BCE) — son and successor of Tiglath-pileser III — marches against Hoshea. Hoshea 'became his vassal and paid him tribute' (<em>wayhî lô ʿeḇed wayyāšeḇ lô minḥāh</em>); the <em>minḥāh</em> (tribute, literally gift-offering) is the same word used for the sacrificial grain offering, suggesting the political tribute-language and the cultic offering-language share a vocabulary of submission. Hoshea's vassalage is initially compliant, continuing the tribute-payment pattern established by Menahem.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Hoshea's conspiracy with 'So king of Egypt' (<em>śōʾ melek miṣrāyim</em>) and withholding of annual tribute triggers Shalmaneser's response. 'So' has been variously identified as Osorkon IV (the last pharaoh of the 22nd dynasty, ruling in Tanis), Tefnakht of Sais (a Delta king), or Sibe the Egyptian commander mentioned in Sargon II's annals. Egypt was entering a period of political fragmentation (the Third Intermediate Period) and was not capable of providing effective military assistance; the appeal to Egypt was strategically futile. Hoshea's arrest and imprisonment before the full siege indicates Shalmaneser may have intercepted the diplomatic correspondence, exposing the conspiracy before Hoshea could fully mobilize against Assyria.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The three-year siege of Samaria (c. 725–722 BCE) is one of the longer sieges recorded in the biblical narrative. Samaria, built on a naturally defensible hill (purchased by Omri, 1 Kgs 16:24), was difficult to take by direct assault; Assyrian siege techniques (ramps, battering rams, siege towers) required time against a well-supplied hilltop city. The three-year resistance indicates significant food and water reserves in the city. Shalmaneser V died during or shortly after the siege; his successor Sargon II claims the actual capture in his own annals (ANET 284-285: 'I besieged and conquered Samaria, led away as booty 27,290 inhabitants of it').</p>",
    "6": "<p>The fall of Samaria (722 BCE) ends the 210-year northern kingdom. The deportation destinations — Halah, the Habor River region in Gozan, and the Median cities — are confirmed in Assyrian texts. Halah is in the region of the upper Tigris; Gozan is the Khabur River basin in northeastern Syria (Tell Halaf in modern Syria); the Median cities are in western Iran (Persia). This triple dispersal across the core of the Assyrian empire was standard practice: deported peoples were resettled far from their homeland, disrupting national identity and reducing revolt risk. The 27,290 deportees of Sargon's annals were likely the skilled, wealthy, and military population; the rural poor remained and formed the base population into which Sargon's imported settlers were placed (vv24-41). The 'ten lost tribes' tradition of Jewish and later Christian speculation begins with this verse.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The Deuteronomist begins the longest theological explanation in Kings (vv7-23), unparalleled in scope in the entire narrative. The explanation opens with the covenantal framework: 'This happened because the Israelites had sinned against the LORD their God, who had brought them out of Egypt' (<em>wayhî kî ḥāṭᵉʾû bᵉnê-Yiśrāʾēl laYHWH ʾelōhêhem hammaʿᵃleh ʾōtām mēʾereṣ miṣrāyim</em>). The Exodus is the defining covenant act; Israel's election and obligation is rooted in YHWH's redemptive initiative. Sin is framed as covenant violation — not merely moral failure but the betrayal of a specific relationship established at Sinai. Worshipping other gods is the fundamental breach (v7b: <em>wayyirᵉʾû ʾelōhîm ʾăḥērîm</em>).</p>",
    "8": "<p>The charge that Israel 'followed the practices of the nations the LORD had driven out before them' (<em>wayyēlᵉḵû bᵉḥuqqôt haggôyim ʾăšer hôrîš YHWH mippᵉnê bᵉnê Yiśrāʾēl</em>) is the Deuteronomistic irony: Israel was to be the replacement population for the nations; instead, Israel adopted the nations' practices and is now itself replaced by imported nations (v24). The divine-expulsion logic that justified the Conquest (Deut 9:4-5 — the nations were driven out for their wickedness, not Israel's righteousness) now applies to Israel: YHWH expels covenant-breakers regardless of their ethnic identity.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Israel 'secretly did things against the LORD their God that were not right' (<em>wayhappāsēq bᵉnê Yiśrāʾēl dᵉḇārîm ʾăšer lōʾ ḵēn ʿal YHWH ʾelōhêhem</em>) — the word <em>hippāsēq</em> (Piel of a root meaning to cover, conceal) indicates the covert nature of the apostasy. The installation of high places 'from the smallest watchtower to the largest fortified city' (<em>mimmigdal nōṣᵉrîm ʿaḏ ʿîr miḇṣār</em>) describes comprehensive geographic coverage: every inhabited site, from the most remote watchpost to the most fortified urban center, had unauthorized cultic installations. The scale of the apostasy matches the scale of the judgment.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The sacred pillars (<em>maṣṣēḇôt</em>) and Asherah poles (<em>ʾăšērîm</em>) are the two most frequently condemned cult installations in the Deuteronomistic literature. <em>Maṣṣēḇôt</em> were standing stones used as markers of divine presence, originally acceptable in the patriarchal period (Gen 28:18) but condemned in Deut 12:3 and 16:22. <em>ʾĂšērîm</em> were wooden poles or trees representing Asherah, the Canaanite mother-goddess and consort of El; archaeological evidence from Kuntillet Ajrud (c. 800 BCE) includes inscriptions referencing 'YHWH of Samaria and his Asherah,' indicating that Asherah veneration was integrated into some forms of YHWH worship. The combination of sacred stones and Asherah poles on 'every high hill and under every green tree' is the standard Deuteronomistic description of full-spectrum Canaanite syncretism.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'They burned offerings at all the high places as the nations had done' (<em>wayhaqṭᵉrû šām bᵉḵol-habbāmôt kaggôyim ʾăšer heglāh YHWH mippᵉnêhem</em>) returns to the governing irony: Israel's behavior mirrors the expelled nations. The phrase <em>wayyaʿᵃśû dᵉḇārîm rāʿîm lᵉḵaʿᵃs ʾet-YHWH</em>, 'they did evil things to provoke the LORD to anger,' introduces the <em>kaʿas</em> (provocation) theme that runs through the Deuteronomistic assessment of the kings; YHWH's response to <em>kaʿas</em> is the withdrawal of protection and the activation of covenant curses.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Israel 'served idols' (<em>wayyaʿaḇdû haggillûlîm</em>) — the word <em>gillûlîm</em> (used 38 times in Ezekiel and here) is a highly polemical term, often understood as a derivation meaning 'dung-pellets' or 'dung-balls,' a deliberate scatological coinage to disparage idols. The explicit divine prohibition — <em>ʾăšer ʾāmar lahem YHWH lōʾ taʿᵃśûn ʾet-haddāḇār hazzeh</em>, 'despite the LORD saying to them: do not do this thing' — frames the idolatry as willful defiance of a clear command rather than ignorance. The Deuteronomistic framework is that Israel had full covenantal knowledge (Deut 4:15-20 explicitly warns against the gods represented by the host of heaven and carved images) and violated it deliberately.</p>",
    "13": "<p>YHWH's prophetic warnings — sent 'through every prophet and seer' (<em>bᵉyaḏ kol nāḇîʾ kol ḥōzeh</em>) — form the second half of the theological indictment: not only was Israel warned by the written law, but YHWH sent continuous prophetic messengers. The specific content of the warning is given: <em>šûḇû middarᵉḵêḵem hārāʿîm wᵉšimrû miṣwōtay ḥuqqôtay kᵉḵol-hattôrāh ʾăšer ṣiwwîtî ʾet ʾăḇōtêḵem wᵉkāʾăšer šālaḥtî ʾalêḵem bᵉyaḏ ʿᵃḇāḏay hanᵉḇîʾîm</em>, 'turn from your evil ways and keep my commandments and statutes — all the law I gave your ancestors, which I sent to you through my servant the prophets.' The prophets are the living voice of the written Torah; their cumulative rejection across 200 years of the northern kingdom is the measure of the apostasy's depth.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Israel 'would not listen but hardened their neck like their ancestors who had not trusted in the LORD their God' (<em>wᵉlōʾ šāmēʿû wayyaqšû ʾet ʿārpām kᵉʿōrep ʾăḇōtām ʾăšer lōʾ heʾěmînû baYHWH ʾelōhêhem</em>). The 'stiff neck' image (<em>qᵉšēh ʿōrep</em>) is first used in Exod 32:9 to describe Israel at the golden-calf incident; the Deuteronomist draws an explicit line from the wilderness apostasy to the northern kingdom's exile, framing the entire history as a single continuous failure. The contrast with faith (<em>heʾěmîn</em> — trusted, believed) is significant: the prophets called for covenant trust; Israel chose autonomy.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Israel 'rejected his statutes and the covenant he had made with their ancestors, and the warnings he had given them; they pursued worthless idols and became worthless themselves' (<em>wayyimᵉʾăsû ʾet ḥuqqāyw wᵉʾet bᵉrîtô ʾăšer kārat ʾet ʾăḇôtām wᵉʾēt ʿēḏwōtāyw ʾăšer hēʿîḏ bām wayyēlᵉḵû ʾaḥᵃrê hahaḇel wayyehbālû</em>). The wordplay on <em>heḇel</em> (vanity, vapor, worthlessness) — 'they pursued hebel and became hebel' — is one of Kings' most pointed theological formulations. Idols are <em>heḇel</em> (the word Ecclesiastes will use for all transient things; the name Abel/Hebel in Gen 4 may carry the same resonance of brevity). Israel became what it worshipped. The surrounding nations' practices that YHWH had forbidden to Israel are the standard of comparison: Israel's holiness was supposed to be the distinction; apostasy erased it.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The full apostasy catalogue: abandoned all YHWH's commandments → cast two metal calves (<em>ʿēgālîm massēḵāh šᵉnayim</em>, Jeroboam's calves of Bethel and Dan, 1 Kgs 12:28) → made an Asherah pole → worshipped the whole host of heaven (<em>kol ṣᵉḇāʾ haššāmayim</em>, astral worship including sun, moon, stars, and the divine council in astral form) → served Baal. The calf worship, Asherah, and astral worship are all attested in the Iron Age archaeological record from Israelite sites: Megiddo, Hazor, Beth-shan, and Tell el-Far'ah North all show evidence of non-YHWH cult objects alongside Israelite material culture. The catalogue is structured to show comprehensive abandonment: no commandment or covenant feature is left untouched.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The final items in the apostasy catalogue — burning children in the fire, practicing divination (<em>qāsam qᵉsāmîm</em>) and sorcery (<em>nāḥaš niḥûšîm</em>), and selling themselves completely to evil (<em>wayyiḥtamkᵉrû lāʿăśôt hārāʿ</em>) — represent the most severe Deuteronomic prohibitions. Child sacrifice is the capital offense of Lev 20:2; divination and sorcery are condemned in Deut 18:10-12 as the defining practices of the nations YHWH expelled; the phrase 'sold themselves to do evil' echoes 1 Kgs 21:20 (Ahab 'sold himself to do evil') — the voluntary, commercial metaphor for sin as self-enslavement. The comprehensive nature of the apostasy list justifies the comprehensive nature of the punishment.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'So the LORD was extremely angry with Israel and expelled them from his sight' (<em>wayyitʾannap YHWH mᵉʾōḏ bᵉYiśrāʾēl wayyᵉsîrēm mēʿal pānāyw lōʾ nišʾar raq šēḇeṭ yᵉhûḏāh lᵉḇaddô</em>). The verb <em>ʾānap</em> (be angry) with the intensifier <em>mᵉʾōḏ</em> (exceedingly) marks the divine anger at its highest register in the narrative. 'Expelled from his sight' (<em>wayyᵉsîrēm mēʿal pānāyw</em>) is the ultimate covenant curse — the loss of divine presence, the reversal of the central covenant promise (Exod 33:14: 'My presence will go with you'). The note that 'only the tribe of Judah remained' is simultaneously a word of partial grace — the Davidic covenant still holds one tribe — and an anticipation of ch 25, where Judah will follow the same trajectory to the same judgment 136 years later.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The addendum — 'Judah also did not obey the commands of the LORD their God but followed the practices that Israel had introduced' (<em>gam Yᵉhûḏāh lōʾ šāmar ʾet miṣwōt YHWH ʾelōhêhem wayyēlᵉḵû bᵉḥuqqôt Yiśrāʾēl ʾăšer ʿāśû</em>) — is a theological footnote that prevents the reader from taking comfort in Judah's survival. Israel pioneered the apostasy; Judah followed. The exile of the north is not just Israel's story but a warning about Judah's trajectory. The Kings account will trace Judah's subsequent spiral through Manasseh's extreme apostasy (ch 21) to Josiah's reform (ch 22-23) to the final Babylonian deportations (ch 24-25).</p>",
    "20": "<p>'The LORD rejected all the descendants of Israel, afflicted them, and handed them over to raiders, until he had expelled them from his sight' (<em>wayyimʾas YHWH bᵉḵol zeraʿ Yiśrāʾēl wayyᵉʿannēm wayyittᵉnēm bᵉyaḏ šōsîm ʿaḏ ʾăšer hišlîḵām mēʿal pānāyw</em>). The verb <em>māʾas</em> (reject, spurn) is used by Hosea (Hos 4:6: 'since you have rejected knowledge, I will reject you from being my priest') and Amos (Amos 2:4: 'because they rejected the law of the LORD') — the prophetic interpretation and the Deuteronomistic explanation use the same vocabulary. The 'raiders' who afflicted Israel during the period of the judges through the kings are reframed as YHWH's instruments of progressive punishment, building toward the final expulsion.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The narrative traces the apostasy back to its origin point: 'when Israel was torn away from the house of David, they made Jeroboam son of Nebat king, and Jeroboam led Israel away from following the LORD and caused them to commit great sin' (<em>kî qāraʿ Yiśrāʾēl mēʿal bêt Dāwîḏ wayyamlîḵû ʾet Yarāḇᵉʿām ben-Nᵉḇāṭ... wayyaddaḥ Yarāḇᵉʿām ʾet Yiśrāʾēl mēʾaḥᵃrê YHWH waheḥĕṭîʾām ḥaṭṭāʾāh gᵉḏôlāh</em>). The Schism (1 Kgs 12) is identified as the moment when the trajectory toward exile became inevitable: not because it was geopolitically destabilizing, but because Jeroboam's substitute cult (the golden calves) permanently redirected northern worship away from Jerusalem and toward an idolatrous alternative. The 210 years from Jeroboam to Hoshea are a single long act of national apostasy rooted in one founding sin.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'The Israelites continued in all the sins Jeroboam had committed; they never turned away from them' (<em>wayyēlᵉḵû bᵉnê Yiśrāʾēl bᵉḵol ḥaṭṭāʾôt Yarāḇᵉʿām ʾăšer ʿāśāh lōʾ sārû mimmennāh</em>) — the climax of the theological explanation's backward reach. The entire history of the northern kings, with their individual variations in wickedness (some worse than others, but none departing from Jeroboam's core sin), is summarized in a single unbroken trajectory. The phrase <em>lōʾ sārû mimmennāh</em> (they did not turn from it) is the negative of the repentance (<em>šûḇ</em>) the prophets consistently called for.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'Until the LORD removed Israel from his sight, just as he had declared through all his servants the prophets. So Israel was carried into exile from their land to Assyria — where they remain to this day' (<em>ʿad ʾăšer-hēsîr YHWH ʾet Yiśrāʾēl mēʿal pānāyw kaʾăšer dibber bᵉyaḏ kol ʿăḇāḏāyw hanᵉḇîʾîm wayyigl Yiśrāʾēl mēʿal ʾadmātô ʾaššûr ʿaḏ hayyôm hazzeh</em>). The phrase 'to this day' (<em>ʿaḏ hayyôm hazzeh</em>) is a historiographic marker indicating the exile was recent and living memory for the text's audience. The Deuteronomistic History was compiled/finalized during or shortly after the Babylonian exile; the northern exile had been a reality for over a century. 'As he declared through all his servants the prophets' ties the historical event to the prophetic corpus — the exile validates the prophets rather than refuting them.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The Assyrian resettlement policy — bringing populations from Babylon, Cuthah, Avva, Hamath, and Sepharvaim to replace the deported Israelites — is part of Sargon II's documented imperial strategy of population interchange. Sargon's annals state: 'the people of the lands conquered by my hands... I settled there; Assyrian administrators I set over them.' The imported populations came from multiple Mesopotamian and Syrian regions, creating a mixed society in the former northern kingdom. The later Samaritan identity grows from this mixed population — the returning exiles under Ezra and Nehemiah viewed Samaritans as disqualified from temple participation (Ezra 4:1-3) precisely because their ancestry was not purely Israelite. The NT Samaritan context (John 4, Luke 10:25-37) inherits this historical and ethnic complexity.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The settler populations' ignorance of 'the requirements of the god of the land' (<em>mišpaṭ ʾelōhê hāʾāreṣ</em>) triggers a lion attack, which YHWH sends. The ANE background is territorial-deity theology (see the Naaman narrative, 5:17): every land had its god, whose requirements had to be met to avoid divine punishment. The lions are a covenant curse from Lev 26:22 ('I will send wild beasts among you which shall rob you of your children and destroy your cattle and make you few in number') — though here applied to settlers rather than Israel. The dynamic is that even the pagan settlers recognize the principle of territorial divine management, while Israel (the people who should have known YHWH's requirements) failed to follow them.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The report to the Assyrian king — that the settler peoples don't know the <em>mišpaṭ ʾelōhê hāʾāreṣ</em> (requirements of the land's god) — uses precisely the territorial-deity framework that Naaman operated within (5:17). The irony is multilayered: non-Israelite settlers recognize that YHWH controls this land and that his requirements must be met; the Israelites who knew his covenant requirements never properly met them. The king of Assyria's practical response (send a priest to teach them) treats YHWH as one of many territorial deities to be managed — a thoroughly ANE-pagan interpretation of the God whose covenant with Israel Israel itself had treated with equal casualness.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The Assyrian king's command — send back one of the exiled priests to live in Bethel and teach the people 'the requirements of the god of the land' — is historically plausible as Assyrian administrative management: deportation policy was pragmatic, and a resident population required religious stability for political management. The specific instruction to send the priest to Bethel is pointed: Bethel was the site of Jeroboam's golden-calf sanctuary (1 Kgs 12:29), the epicenter of the northern kingdom's original apostasy. The priest who teaches YHWH worship there is inheriting a fundamentally compromised cult site.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The returning Israelite priest settles in Bethel and teaches the people 'how to worship the LORD' (<em>wayyᵉhi mᵉlammēḏ ʾōtām ʾêḵ yîrᵉʾû ʾet YHWH</em>). The verb <em>yārēʾ</em> (fear, revere) is the standard covenant-fear vocabulary; the priest presumably teaches some form of YHWH worship. However, the content of his teaching is compromised by two factors: (1) the Bethel location was associated with the calf-worship that the Deuteronomist considered fundamental apostasy; (2) the settlers continue their own deity practices alongside (vv29-33). The teaching produces syncretism, not conversion.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The imported nations manufacture their own gods — <em>wayhî maʿᵃśēh kol gôy wᵉgôy ʾelōhêhem</em>, 'each nation made its gods' — and install them in the high-place shrines (<em>bêt habbāmôt</em>) the Samaritans had built. The high-place infrastructure that the Israelites had built for syncretic YHWH worship is now repurposed for purely pagan worship by the immigrant populations. Each settler community imports its own national deity into the Israelite sacred geography, creating a religious patchwork that reverses the Conquest's purification of the land's cult sites.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The Babylonians made Succoth-benoth (<em>Sukkôt bᵉnôt</em> — possibly 'the booths of the daughters,' a name that may relate to a Babylonian astral deity, possibly Zarpanitum, consort of Marduk); the Cutheans made Nergal (the Babylonian underworld deity, god of pestilence and the dead, worshipped at Cutha/Tell Ibrahim in modern Iraq); the Hamathites made Ashima (<em>ʾăšîmāʾ</em> — a deity attested in Aramaic inscriptions from Hamath, possibly a form of Ishtar or a local deity). These deities are largely confirmed in cuneiform and Aramaic sources; the biblical naming preserves historical memory of the specific cult communities that settled in the former northern territory.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The Avvites made Nibhaz (<em>niḇḥaz</em> — possibly a dog-deity, corresponding to the Elamite deity Ibnahaza or a corruption of Anubis) and Tartak (unidentified; possibly an Aramaean deity). The Sepharvites burned their children to Adrammelech (<em>ʾaḏrammeleḵ</em> — possibly a form of the Mesopotamian deity Adad combined with melek, 'king') and Anammelech (<em>ʿanammeleḵ</em> — possibly Anu + melek, the Mesopotamian sky god). The child sacrifice practices of the Sepharvites mirror Ahaz's child sacrifice to Molech (16:3), creating an ironic parallel: the sin that characterized Judah's worst king is now practiced by pagan settlers in the former northern territory. The land that could not tolerate Israel's sins is now occupied by peoples practicing the same or worse sins.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The settlers 'professed to fear the LORD' (<em>wayhû yᵉrēʾîm ʾet YHWH</em>) while appointing their own priests for the high places. The appointment of non-Levitical, ethnically mixed priests for the high-place shrines parallels Jeroboam's appointment of non-Levitical priests (1 Kgs 12:31, 13:33); both represent the principle that the cult can be managed by whoever is politically convenient rather than whoever is covenantally designated. The fear vocabulary here is the language of pagan territorial-deity management, not the covenant-fear the law demands.</p>",
    "33": "<p>'They worshiped the LORD, but they also served their own gods in the way of the nations from which they had come' (<em>ʾet YHWH hāyû yᵉrēʾîm wᵉʾet ʾelōhêhem hāyû ʿōḇdîm kᵉmišpaṭ haggôyim ʾăšer heglû ʾōtām miššām</em>). This is the defining description of Samaritan religion: syncretistic fear of YHWH combined with ethnic-deity worship. The phrase 'in the way of the nations' (<em>kᵉmišpaṭ haggôyim</em>) uses the same <em>mišpaṭ</em> (requirement, custom, legal standard) that the settlers initially lacked (v25-26): they now have a <em>mišpaṭ</em> for YHWH alongside their ethnic <em>mišpaṭ</em>. The result is a syncretistic religion indistinguishable from the Canaanite cult the Conquest was meant to remove.</p>",
    "34": "<p>'To this day they follow their original practices. They do not truly fear the LORD or observe the statutes, ordinances, laws, and commandments he gave to the descendants of Jacob, whom he named Israel' (<em>ʿaḏ hayyôm hazzeh hēm ʿōśîm kammišpāṭîm hārišōnîm ʾênām yᵉrēʾîm ʾet YHWH wᵉʾênām ʿōśîm kᵉḥuqqōtām ûkᵉmišpāṭêhem ûḵattôrāh ûḵammmiṣwāh ʾăšer ṣiwwāh YHWH ʾet bᵉnê yaʿᵃqōḇ ʾăšer śām šᵉmô Yiśrāʾēl</em>). The use of the name Israel — 'descendants of Jacob whom he named Israel' — asserts that the name Israel belongs properly to the covenant community descended from Jacob, not to the mixed settler population of Samaria. This naming-assertion anticipates the post-exilic controversy over who constitutes true Israel (Ezra 4, Neh 13).</p>",
    "35": "<p>YHWH's covenant command (vv35-39) is cited in full as the standard the settlers are failing to meet. The prohibition — 'you must not worship other gods or bow down to them or serve them or sacrifice to them' (<em>lōʾ tîrᵉʾû ʾelōhîm ʾăḥērîm wᵉlōʾ tišᵉtaḥᵃwû lāhem wᵉlōʾ taʿᵃḇdûm wᵉlōʾ tizbᵉḥû lāhem</em>) — restates the first and second commandments of the Decalogue (Exod 20:3-5). The fourfold prohibition (fear, bow down, serve, sacrifice) covers the full range of cultic acts; the Samaritan settlers' practices (vv32-33) violate all four. The covenant is cited not to condemn the settlers (they were not party to it) but to define what true fear of YHWH looks like, in contrast to their syncretistic practice.</p>",
    "36": "<p>'Rather, fear the LORD who brought you out of Egypt with great power and an outstretched arm' (<em>kî ʾim ʾet YHWH ʾăšer heʿᵃlāh ʾetḵem mēʾereṣ miṣrāyim bᵉḵōaḥ gāḏôl ûḇizrôaʿ nᵉṭûyāh ʾōtô tîrᵉʾû wᵉlô tišᵉtaḥᵃwû wᵉlô tizbᵉḥû</em>). The Exodus formulation is the defining ground of Israelite covenant obligation: YHWH's election-act creates the exclusive covenant claim. The 'outstretched arm' (<em>zᵉrôaʿ nᵉṭûyāh</em>) is standard Exodus liturgical language (Exod 6:6, Deut 4:34, 5:15, 7:19). The settlers who had no part in the Exodus cannot respond to this appeal from within; the text's citation of it functions more as an indictment of Israel's failure to respond than as a command to the settlers.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The comprehensive command — observe forever the statutes, ordinances, laws, and commandments YHWH wrote for his people — uses four distinct legal terms: <em>ḥuqqôt</em> (statutes), <em>mišpāṭîm</em> (ordinances/judgments), <em>tôrāh</em> (law/instruction), <em>miṣwāh</em> (commandment). This legal quadruple also appears in 2 Chr 19:10 and reflects the Deuteronomistic understanding that the Torah has a comprehensive character: not just commandments or just statutes, but the entire integrated legal-covenantal deposit. The command to observe them 'forever' (<em>kol hayyāmîm</em>, all the days) excludes the possibility of situational non-compliance.</p>",
    "38": "<p>'Do not forget the covenant I have made with you' (<em>wᵉhabbᵉrît ʾăšer kāratî ʾittᵉḵem lōʾ tišᵉkāḥû</em>) is the central anti-forgetting command of Deuteronomic theology. Deut 4:9, 6:12, and 8:11 repeatedly command Israel not to forget YHWH and his covenant; the prophets repeatedly charge Israel with forgetting (Hos 8:14, 13:6). The history of the northern kingdom is precisely the history of covenantal forgetting: the Torah was not read publicly, the Passover was not kept (until Josiah, 23:22), and the covenant obligations were treated as optional rather than constitutive of national identity.</p>",
    "39": "<p>'Fear only the LORD your God, and he will rescue you from all your enemies' (<em>kî ʾim ʾet YHWH ʾelōhêḵem tîrᵉʾû wᵉhûʾ yaṣṣîl ʾetḵem mikkol ʾōyᵉḇêḵem</em>) is the covenant's positive promise: monolatrous fear of YHWH yields military protection. The irony is that Israel sought protection from Assyria through tribute (Menahem), through coalition politics (Pekah), and through Egyptian alliance (Hoshea) — every avenue except covenant fidelity. The verse anticipates Hezekiah's vindication (ch 18-19), where singular fear of YHWH (rather than Assyrian tribute or Egyptian alliance) results in miraculous deliverance from Sennacherib.</p>",
    "40": "<p>'But they would not listen; they kept to their old ways' (<em>wᵉlōʾ šāmēʿû kî ʾim kᵉmišpāṭām hārîʾšôn hēm ʿōśîm</em>). The verse closes the covenant-exposition section with the same stubborn non-response that the text attributed to Israel in v14: <em>wᵉlōʾ šāmēʿû</em> (they did not listen). The settlers who replaced the Israelites exhibit the same fundamental orientation — following original practices rather than YHWH's covenant — that characterized the Israelites throughout the northern kingdom's history. The replacements are not an improvement; the land continues under the same spiritual pattern.</p>",
    "41": "<p>'So these peoples worshiped the LORD but also served their own idols. Their children and grandchildren do the same today, just as their ancestors did' (<em>wayhû haggôyim hāʾēlleh yᵉrēʾîm ʾet YHWH wᵉʾet pᵉsilêhem hāyû ʿōḇdîm gam bᵉnêhem ûḇnê bᵉnêhem kaʾăšer ʿāśû ʾăḇōtām hēm ʿōśîm ʿaḏ hayyôm hazzeh</em>). The closing verse of ch 17 is simultaneously a historical statement about the Samaritan settlers and an anticipation of the Samaritan-Jewish controversy that runs from Ezra through the NT. The 'to this day' again connects the narrative to the author's present. The Samaritan woman at the well (John 4:20: 'Our fathers worshipped on this mountain, but you say Jerusalem is the place') and the healed Samaritan's gratitude (Luke 17:16) both operate against the background of this centuries-old religious ambiguity that v41 captures: part-worship of YHWH, part-worship of other gods, established as the inherited pattern of the land.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', '2kings')
    merge_comm(c, KINGS2)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '2kings', c)
    count = sum(len(v) for v in KINGS2.values())
    print(f'2kings mkt-context: wrote {count} verses across ch 15-17')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
